    "introSummary": "Google Sheets automations often seem fine until a row is edited out of order, a tab gets renamed, or an update lands on the wrong record because the row reference was never resolved correctly.\n\nGetForked maps the workflow you already run, identifies where Zapier is unreliable, and matches you with an approved builder to replace brittle sheet-to-sheet or sheet-to-system logic with owned connectors, review controls, and handover-ready documentation.",
    "heroSummary": "Google Sheets automations often seem fine until a row is edited out of order, a tab gets renamed, or an update lands on the wrong record because the row reference was never resolved correctly.\n\nGetForked maps the workflow you already run, identifies where Zapier is unreliable, and matches you with an approved builder to replace brittle sheet-to-sheet or sheet-to-system logic with owned connectors, review controls, and handover-ready documentation.",
    "problemSummary": "Most Google Sheets workflows running through Zapier follow a familiar pattern. A new contact row is added at the bottom of a tracker sheet and should start a Zap, or a row is edited in one monitored column and the workflow is supposed to write back to the same sheet, mirror data into another spreadsheet, or update a downstream system. That setup looks simple until the process starts depending on stable row identity across changing sheets.\n\nThe breakage usually comes from operational details, not from one dramatic failure. A unique identifier such as email, customer ID, or reference number may exist in both the source and target sheet, but the value is not actually unique in practice.",
    "replacementSummary": "A sturdier replacement treats Google Sheets as a row-based system that needs identity checks, schema checks, and explicit write rules. The implementation validates which spreadsheet and worksheet should be touched, confirms the expected headers are still present, and waits until the monitored row has the required cells populated before any downstream write happens. For update logic, the safest pattern is trigger -> lookup by unique key -> update by Row ID, because a lookup step can resolve a stable identifier for the exact row that should be changed.\n\nIt also accounts for Google Sheets behavior that basic Zaps often hide.",
    "uniqueContentAngle": "Replace Zapier workflows that pipe data into/from Google Sheets with direct API connectors or custom dashboards",
    "bodyHtml": "<h2>Google Sheets workflows that usually hit limits first</h2>\n<p>A common pattern starts with one sheet row and turns into a real operational process. A row added event may assign an owner, sync data into another spreadsheet, update a CRM, or create work in another system.</p>\n<p>The problem is that Google Sheets behaves like a flexible document while the workflow expects database-style consistency. People insert rows, rename tabs, duplicate sheets, and change headers, so the automation can lose track of which row, range, or cells it is acting on.</p>\n<p>That is why ownership matters. A replacement should define the spreadsheet, the tab, the matching key, and whether the process should update an existing record or append a new one.</p>\n<h3>Lead tracker write-backs</h3>\n<p>In many sales teams, a row is edited when a rep changes a trigger column from review to ready. A safer implementation waits until the required cells are complete, confirms that the email or customer ID maps to one record, and updates the matched row instead of relying on row position.</p>\n<h3>Cross-sheet reconciliation</h3>\n<p>One sheet may capture intake while another holds operational status. If a row is added or updated in one sheet and should be mirrored or corrected in another sheet using the same key, the replacement needs explicit row identity and duplicate handling before any sync runs.</p>\n<h3>Shared reporting sheets</h3>\n<p>When the source file lives in Team Drive, missed detections can come from the trigger choice itself. A sturdier setup uses the Team Drive-specific trigger path and logs what changed so reporting data does not drift quietly.</p>\n<h2>What to include in the scoped brief</h2>\n<p>A useful brief should describe the real workflow, not just list apps. Name every Google Sheets spreadsheet involved, the tabs in each file, the headers that matter, and which row starts the process.</p>\n<p>You should also identify the real key used to match records. If email, customer ID, or reference number exists in both the source and target sheet, say whether duplicates already exist and how those exceptions should be handled.</p>\n<p>Write behavior matters too. Some actions should update an existing row, while others should append to the next detected table row. That distinction is important because Google Sheets append requires spreadsheet ID, range, and valueInputOption; append always adds to subsequent rows after the detected table, not an arbitrary fixed cell.</p>\n<h3>Identity and mapping details</h3>\n<p>List the unique identifier, the columns used in lookups, the fields written back, and whether updates must use the Row ID returned by a Lookup Spreadsheet Row step. Include sample rows for both valid and invalid cases.</p>\n<h3>Trigger conditions</h3>\n<p>Document whether the event is really row added, cell changed, or range updated in practice. If a row is edited in a monitored column, note exactly which column starts processing and which edits should be ignored.</p>\n<h3>Operational exceptions</h3>\n<p>Call out known bad cases such as non-unique keys, partially filled rows, inserted columns, renamed tabs, and Team Drive access quirks. Those details are what separate a stable build from a cosmetic rewrite.</p>\n<h2>The control points an owned implementation should add</h2>\n<p>A direct Google Sheets integration should not treat every trigger as immediately ready for downstream work. It needs validation that checks whether the row is complete enough to trust, whether the key is unique, and whether the target structure still matches the expected schema.</p>\n<p>It also needs explicit write rules. Updating an existing record should use a stable identifier, while create behavior should be deliberate about append semantics and race conditions when multiple writes land close together.</p>\n<p>Finally, it should leave a usable audit trail. Teams should be able to see which spreadsheets, sheets, rows, ranges, and cells were involved in a run without reverse-engineering a failed Zap.</p>\n<h3>Validation before sync</h3>\n<p>Validation before sync is critical for finance or sales sheets because an incomplete row can trigger a bad handoff. A direct workflow can hold processing until the required cells are present and then continue.</p>\n<h3>Protection against structure drift</h3>\n<p>Sheet structure changes break brittle mappings quickly. Owned logic can verify expected headers and tab names before writing, then stop safely if someone inserted a column or changed the layout.</p>\n<h3>Safer update targeting</h3>\n<p>If the process needs to find an existing customer row and update that exact row, the implementation should resolve the match first and only then perform the update with the returned identifier. That avoids the common mistake where the Row field is not a custom Row ID from a prior lookup.</p>\n<h2>Why handover matters once the workflow is replaced</h2>\n<p>The point of replacing a fragile sheet workflow is not just to stop breakage today. It is to give your team a process they can inspect, understand, and change without relearning the same failure pattern every quarter.</p>\n<p>A proper handover should include trigger rules, lookup logic, field maps, append versus update behavior, Team Drive notes, review criteria, and where to inspect failed items or replay safe retries.</p>\n<p>That makes the workflow easier to own internally, whether the next change is a new tab, an added downstream system, or a revised set of required cells.</p>\n<h3>What documentation should cover</h3>\n<p>Expect a clear inventory of spreadsheets, sheets, rows, key fields, ranges, cells, credentials, and exception paths. The documentation should explain how row identity is established and how writes are protected against duplicates or structure drift.</p>\n<h3>What the dashboard should show</h3>\n<p>If the replacement includes an internal dashboard, it should show pending reviews, rejected matches, successful updates, and failed writes by spreadsheet and worksheet. That is far more useful than only seeing that a task did or did not run.</p>\n<h3>When staying lightweight is still fine</h3>\n<p>If the workflow is just a simple notification from one stable sheet and manual verification is easy, there may be no reason to replace it yet. The case for owned logic gets stronger as row matching, write-back safety, and auditability become operational requirements.</p>",
