    "introSummary": "Slack workflows often start with a practical trigger: a message lands in a channel, someone adds a reaction, or a file is shared. They get harder to trust when thread replies are missed, a post goes to the wrong destination, or a polling-based check arrives later than the team expects.\n\nGetForked defines the workflow before implementation begins. We turn the Slack process into a scoped brief, then match you with an approved builder who can implement direct Slack API handling for channels, messages, threads, users, and file events with documented rules, exception paths, and handover-ready ownership.",
    "heroSummary": "Slack workflows often start with a practical trigger: a message lands in a channel, someone adds a reaction, or a file is shared. They get harder to trust when thread replies are missed, a post goes to the wrong destination, or a polling-based check arrives later than the team expects.\n\nGetForked defines the workflow before implementation begins. We turn the Slack process into a scoped brief, then match you with an approved builder who can implement direct Slack API handling for channels, messages, threads, users, and file events with documented rules, exception paths, and handover-ready ownership.",
    "problemSummary": "Slack automation usually becomes unreliable for operational reasons, not because the original use case was bad. A team may start with a new message in a selected public channel, a reaction added to a message, or a file event, then expand that trigger into incident routing, approvals, summaries, or updates in another system. Once that happens, the workflow has to respect Slack’s actual object model. It needs to know whether it is processing a top-level post or a reply, whether the target is a public channel, private channel, direct message, or multiparty direct message, and whether the connected account can really access that destination.",
    "replacementSummary": "A stronger replacement starts by defining the event contract in Slack terms instead of in Zap steps. The implementation decides whether the start condition is New Public Message Posted Anywhere in a public Slack channel, New Message Posted to Channel in a specific #channel, a reaction event, or a file-related event, then applies separate handling rules for channels, messages, threads, users, and file objects. For thread-aware workflows, it stores Slack message IDs: `ts` for the message timestamp and `thread_ts` for the parent thread timestamp so parent posts and replies are handled intentionally.",
    "uniqueContentAngle": "Replace Zapier notification and workflow bots with custom Slack integrations using the Slack API directly",
    "bodyHtml": "<h2>Slack workflows that commonly start in Zapier</h2>\n<p>Many teams begin with a straightforward Slack rule: when a message is posted, do something else. In practice that often means routing a support issue, starting an approval after a reaction, notifying another team, or processing a newly shared file.</p>\n<p>Those use cases are valid, but Slack is not one flat stream. It has channels, messages, threads, users, and file objects, and the workflow gets brittle when those are treated as interchangeable.</p>\n<h3>Channel message intake</h3>\n<p>A common starting point is New Message Posted to Channel in a specific #channel. That is fine for simple intake, but if the process later needs to separate top-level posts from replies, the implementation has to carry the right Slack IDs forward.</p>\n<h3>Workspace-wide monitoring</h3>\n<p>Some teams use New Public Message Posted Anywhere in a public Slack channel to watch broad activity. That widens coverage, but it also raises the chance of duplicate handling, bad channel routing, and noisy follow-up if targeting rules are loose.</p>\n<h3>Reaction and file follow-up</h3>\n<p>A reaction can mean approve, escalate, assign, or summarize. A file upload can mean review, archive, or classify. Each signal needs explicit rules about who can trigger it, what Slack object is being acted on, and where the result should be sent.</p>\n<h2>The Slack details that usually break trust</h2>\n<p>The hardest Slack failures are usually quiet. The workflow appears to run, but it acts on the wrong object, posts into the wrong conversation, or misses an event users expected to be immediate.</p>\n<p>That is why a replacement needs to be built around Slack’s operating model rather than a generic automation pattern.</p>\n<h3>Thread boundaries</h3>\n<p>If the workflow should react to replies, it must distinguish a reply from the parent post. Slack message IDs: `ts` for the message timestamp and `thread_ts` for the parent thread timestamp are the practical boundary. Without them, reply logic and parent-post logic get mixed together.</p>\n<h3>Conversation access</h3>\n<p>Slack conversation targets include public channels, private channels, direct messages, and multiparty direct messages. A workflow that assumes they all behave the same way will eventually run into missing access, incomplete visibility, or bad routing.</p>\n<h3>Posting constraints</h3>\n<p>Slack message posting is rate limited to roughly 1 chat message per second per channel, with short bursts allowed but sustained excess causing throttling. If several source events fan out into one channel, the workflow needs pacing, retries, and message ordering controls.</p>\n<h3>Polling versus immediate delivery</h3>\n<p>Zapier notes that some Slack triggers are instant while search-based triggers are polling. If the process depends on immediate acknowledgment or fast routing, a polling-based design creates the wrong expectations during testing and production.</p>\n<h2>What to put in the replacement brief</h2>\n<p>A good brief makes the Slack workflow testable before anyone writes code. It should define the start event, the object boundary, the allowed conversation targets, and the expected action for both normal and exception cases.</p>\n<p>This is where GetForked is useful in a specific way: we shape the brief so the matched builder is implementing a defined workflow with operating rules, not trying to invent those rules mid-project.</p>\n<h3>Define the start event precisely</h3>\n<p>Specify whether the workflow begins with a message posted, mention triggered, thread reply, reaction added, or file event. If the current setup relies on search, note that search-based triggers follow a polling loop instead of immediate event delivery.</p>\n<h3>List the required identifiers</h3>\n<p>Call out the exact values that must be stored or forwarded: channel, user, Slack message IDs: `ts` for the message timestamp and `thread_ts` for the parent thread timestamp, plus any downstream ticket or case IDs that need to stay linked.</p>\n<h3>Document routing and access rules</h3>\n<p>State which public channels, private channels, direct messages, or multiparty direct messages are in scope, who owns permissions, and what should happen if the app loses access or the target cannot be found.</p>\n<h3>Write the exception policy</h3>\n<p>Include how to handle throttling, retries, missing channels, malformed file events, duplicate reactions, and cases that should stop for manual review instead of posting automatically.</p>\n<h2>What a handover-ready Slack build should leave behind</h2>\n<p>A useful replacement is not just working code. It is a Slack workflow your team can inspect, test, and change without reverse-engineering a long chain of automation steps.</p>\n<p>That means the final delivery should make operational ownership clear from the start.</p>\n<h3>Operational notes</h3>\n<p>You should receive a plain-language description of the trigger, routing logic, channel scope, thread behavior, posting limits, retry rules, and any file-processing branches.</p>\n<h3>Testing guidance</h3>\n<p>The handover should explain how to test top-level messages, thread replies, reaction events, file shares, channel access failures, and high-volume posting scenarios without guessing which Slack object is in play.</p>\n<h3>Ownership after launch</h3>\n<p>The replacement should identify where logs live, who can change target channels, how credentials are managed, and what to do when errors like channel_not_found or rate-limit responses appear.</p>",
