    "bodyHtml": "<h2>Mailchimp workflows that commonly outgrow Zapier</h2>\n<p>The pattern usually begins with a contact event outside Mailchimp. A form submission, CRM update, purchase, webinar registration, or support action sends data from an external system so a subscriber can be created or updated in an audience. After that, Mailchimp relies on the stored subscriber email address, tags, and merge field values to personalize an email and determine who belongs in a segment.</p>\n<p>That arrangement becomes fragile when more than one source can update the same subscriber. One system may own plan status, another may own consent, and another may assign campaign tags. Without explicit ownership rules, Mailchimp receives conflicting updates and the audience no longer reflects the business rules the team thinks it is using.</p>\n<h3>Lead and signup intake</h3>\n<p>A signup flow often needs to create or update a subscriber in Mailchimp immediately after a form or product event. The replacement should verify the subscriber email address, choose the correct audience, and reject the write when a required merge field is missing or not valid for that audience.</p>\n<h3>CRM profile sync</h3>\n<p>A CRM may send sales region, lifecycle stage, plan type, or owner details into Mailchimp. That stays reliable only when the workflow defines which fields the CRM is allowed to overwrite and which Mailchimp values should remain protected.</p>\n<h3>Campaign eligibility updates</h3>\n<p>When a contact action changes tags, merge fields, or unsubscribe status, the workflow should update those controls in a deliberate order and confirm that the resulting audience state still matches campaign targeting rules before the next send.</p>\n<h2>What to define in the replacement scope</h2>\n<p>A useful replacement scope treats Mailchimp as a contact data model, not just as an app destination. It should identify each audience, every source that can create or update a subscriber, the required subscriber email address rule, and every tag or merge field used for personalization, segmentation, or suppression.</p>\n<p>The brief should also define failure behavior. If a value is invalid, an audience field is missing, or a route points to the wrong audience, the workflow should stop with a clear exception instead of silently creating bad audience data.</p>\n<h3>Audience structure and routing</h3>\n<p>Document whether the business should consolidate around one audience or keep multiple audiences for a defined reason. This matters because Mailchimp recommends 1 primary audience and using tags, groups, or segments to organize contacts, because separate audiences do not share contact data.</p>\n<h3>Field definitions and mapping rules</h3>\n<p>List default fields such as FNAME, LNAME, ADDRESS, and PHONE, plus every custom field used by external systems. Note that Mailchimp and Mailchimp Developer docs use slightly different terms: audience fields in the app and merge fields in the API.</p>\n<h3>Protected states and exception handling</h3>\n<p>The scope should state which fields can never be overwritten automatically, especially unsubscribe and suppression states. If an external source sends conflicting data, the workflow should hold the update, log it, and route it for review.</p>\n<h2>Mailchimp risks that are easy to miss in QA</h2>\n<p>Many Mailchimp issues look small during setup and become expensive only after a campaign goes out. A contact may exist, a tag may be present, and the last update may appear successful, while the actual audience placement or merge field value still makes the subscriber unusable for the intended segment.</p>\n<p>QA also fails when teams test only with preview data. Mailchimp behavior around personalization and segmentation needs validation against real subscriber records, real audience membership, and real status changes.</p>\n<h3>Audience mismatch</h3>\n<p>If the workflow writes to the wrong audience, the subscriber exists in Mailchimp but not where the downstream campaign expects to find that person. This is especially common when multiple teams maintain separate audiences without a clear routing rule.</p>\n<h3>Merge field validation failure</h3>\n<p>Mailchimp merge fields are typed and validated; examples include text, number, radio, dropdown, and date, and text values are truncated to 255 bytes. The replacement should enforce those constraints before attempting the write.</p>\n<h3>Misleading preview checks</h3>\n<p>Live merge tags work in real sends but not in test emails, making preview-only QA misleading. Good testing uses actual contact records, real tag and segment conditions, and unsubscribe scenarios that reflect live campaign behavior.</p>\n<h2>What good handover looks like after replacement</h2>\n<p>The rebuilt workflow should be understandable by the marketing and operations team that uses it. Handover should show what creates a subscriber, what updates a subscriber, how audience selection works, which source owns each merge field, and how tags and unsubscribe changes are handled.</p>\n<p>It should also make future changes safe. If a new CRM property or form field is added later, the team should know where to update the mapping, how to test it, and what validation rules must pass before the new field can affect an audience.</p>\n<h3>Documentation tied to real Mailchimp behavior</h3>\n<p>Useful documentation includes source events, audience routing rules, subscriber status handling, field definitions, tag logic, retry behavior, and exception paths. It should also explain terminology differences between Mailchimp app settings and API calls.</p>\n<h3>Runbooks for common failures</h3>\n<p>The team should know how to inspect a failed Mailchimp write, replay a safe update, verify that the subscriber landed in the correct audience, and confirm that the right tag or merge field now appears on the record.</p>\n<h3>Phased migration instead of a full cutover</h3>\n<p>Many teams do not need to replace every Zap immediately. A practical migration keeps low-risk notifications in place while moving the shared Mailchimp sync paths that control audience data, segmentation inputs, and unsubscribe integrity first.</p>",
