    "introSummary": "A lot of Trello automation starts with a simple rule on one board: when a card appears in a named list, add a checklist, apply a label, assign someone, post a comment, or set a due date.\n\nProblems show up when that same process starts relying on Trello board and list membership, cross-board handoffs, Power-Up data, or activity triggers that do not behave the way the team assumes.",
    "heroSummary": "A lot of Trello automation starts with a simple rule on one board: when a card appears in a named list, add a checklist, apply a label, assign someone, post a comment, or set a due date.\n\nProblems show up when that same process starts relying on Trello board and list membership, cross-board handoffs, Power-Up data, or activity triggers that do not behave the way the team assumes.",
    "problemSummary": "Trello is usually easy to trust when the process stays board-local and the card lifecycle is clear. One card is created in Intake, a checklist is added, a label is applied, a teammate is assigned, and the card moves through lists on the same board until Done. That kind of setup maps well to a Trello automation rule/button/command in Butler or a straightforward Zapier Trello trigger/action.\n\nThe failures start when the workflow quietly depends on Trello behavior that is narrower than the team expects. A move between boards is not handled like a same-board list change. A trigger watching broad activity can miss events because the connected account lacks Trello board and list membership.",
    "replacementSummary": "A solid replacement starts by defining the exact Trello event boundary before anything else runs. It decides whether the workflow should begin from card creation in one named list, a same-board list move, a new comment, a new label, a checklist change, or a due date action. It then enforces scope around the actual board, list, membership, and card data required for that event.\n\nIn practice, the design uses the fact that Card lifecycle changes within one board, such as moving from In Progress to Done, are reliable trigger candidates for Zapier or Butler, while treating cross-board movement as a separate handoff model.",
    "uniqueContentAngle": "Replace Zapier Trello automations with custom project tracking tools or native Trello Power-Ups",
    "bodyHtml": "<h2>Trello setups that often outgrow a Zap</h2>\n<p>Many teams start with a practical board rule and only later discover the edge cases. A Trello card is created in one list, a checklist is added, a member is assigned, a label is applied, a comment is posted, and a due date is set. That is still a strong fit for board-local automation.</p>\n<p>The strain appears when the card is also meant to update another tool, change behavior based on comments, or move between boards while keeping the same business meaning. At that point, Trello event semantics matter more than the original team expected.</p>\n<h3>Intake and support operations</h3>\n<p>A support queue often starts with one Trello board where every new card in Intake gets a checklist, label, owner, and due date. That stays manageable until one step depends on moving work to another board, because a board-to-board transfer does not behave like a simple list move on the same board.</p>\n<h3>Completion rules on one board</h3>\n<p>Completion logic is usually much safer when it stays local to one board. When a card is moved to Done on the same board, archiving the card, clearing the due date, or marking related work complete is often better handled in Butler than in an external chain.</p>\n<h3>Boards driven by Power-Up data</h3>\n<p>Some teams route work based on a custom field, not on the visible card title or list name. In those cases, a Trello card, checklist, label, due date, and comment may all be present while the real decision field is missing from the Zap payload.</p>\n<h2>Operational details a replacement should control</h2>\n<p>A proper replacement should define the workflow in Trello terms first: which board event matters, which list names are authoritative, what Trello board and list membership is required, and which card fields must exist before any action runs. That avoids building logic on top of assumptions that Trello itself does not guarantee.</p>\n<p>It should also split in-board automation from external sync. Butler is often the right tool for card updates that never leave Trello. API-backed workflow logic is usually better for logging, external system updates, exception handling, and checks that depend on data not exposed in standard Zap steps.</p>\n<h3>Membership and visibility</h3>\n<p>Zapier requires an active Trello account and access to the boards involved. If the connected account is not a member of the relevant board or cannot see the relevant cards, triggers can miss card activity even though the team assumes everything is covered.</p>\n<h3>Same-board moves versus board handoffs</h3>\n<p>Move Card to List in Zapier only applies within the same board. If the process assumes a card will keep the same move-trigger path across boards, the workflow needs a separate handoff design instead of treating every move as one continuous list transition.</p>\n<h3>Limits and retry design</h3>\n<p>Trello API limits are 300 requests per 10 seconds per API key and 100 requests per 10 seconds per token. On active boards, the replacement should include queueing, backoff, and clear logging so comment bursts, label updates, and card changes do not fail invisibly.</p>\n<h2>What to include in the scoped brief and handover</h2>\n<p>The brief should describe the real operating workflow, not just the software steps. It should identify the Trello board, list names, trigger events, card states, required card data, checklist actions, labels, comments, due date rules, and what happens when a card cannot be processed.</p>\n<p>A good handover should also clarify ownership. If Butler, a direct API connector, and another system all update the same card, your team needs a clear explanation of which tool changes what, where errors are reviewed, and how future board changes are managed.</p>\n<h3>Document every trigger and exception</h3>\n<p>Ask for a plain-English description of what starts the workflow, what stops it, what data each step depends on, and how failures are reported. Someone new to the team should be able to follow what happens when a card is created, moved, labeled, assigned, commented on, or archived.</p>\n<h3>Plan for board changes</h3>\n<p>Trello boards evolve constantly. Lists are renamed, labels are repurposed, due date rules change, and new boards get added. The handover should explain how monitored lists, membership assumptions, and downstream mappings are updated without breaking the workflow.</p>\n<h3>Keep the simple parts simple</h3>\n<p>Not every step should be rebuilt. Board-local creation events, such as creating a card in a named list, are good trigger points for auto-checklist, auto-label, or auto-assign steps, and those can remain in Butler or Zapier when they are stable and easy to verify.</p>",
