    "introSummary": "Google Calendar and Notion usually get connected in two directions: a new Google Calendar event should create a Notion database item, and a Notion database item should create or update a Google Calendar event.\n\nThat setup becomes unreliable when the target is not a Notion page in a database/data source, the Notion database schema cannot hold the calendar fields, or event creation is attempted without both required start and end values. GetForked scopes the exact workflow, then matches you with an approved builder to deliver an owned integration your team can run and maintain.",
    "heroSummary": "Google Calendar and Notion usually get connected in two directions: a new Google Calendar event should create a Notion database item, and a Notion database item should create or update a Google Calendar event.\n\nThat setup becomes unreliable when the target is not a Notion page in a database/data source, the Notion database schema cannot hold the calendar fields, or event creation is attempted without both required start and end values. GetForked scopes the exact workflow, then matches you with an approved builder to deliver an owned integration your team can run and maintain.",
    "problemSummary": "This pairing usually fails through field-shape mistakes, missing permissions, and update noise rather than a single visible outage. A Google Calendar event can reach Notion but lose title, time, attendees, or status because the Notion database lacks matching properties. A Notion database item can try to create a calendar event from loose page content instead of structured properties, which produces the wrong event shape or no event at all. Trust drops when people have to open the Google Calendar event, compare it to the Notion database item, and manually decide which system holds the correct version.",
