    "uniqueContentAngle": "Replace Zapier sync between Notion and Google Calendar with a direct two-way integration",
    "bodyHtml": "<h2>The two Google Calendar and Notion workflows most teams are actually running</h2>\n<p>This is usually not one integration. It is two separate jobs that happen to involve the same tools. First, a new Google Calendar event should create a Notion database item. Second, a Notion database item should create or update a Google Calendar event.</p>\n<p>Those two jobs need different controls. Calendar-to-Notion depends on the destination database schema and property mapping. Notion-to-Calendar depends on structured date fields, complete event timing, and clear rules for whether a page update should create a new event or modify an existing one.</p>\n<h3>Google Calendar into a Notion database</h3>\n<p>This flow works best when the Notion database already contains properties for event title, date, start, end, attendees, owner, and status. If those properties are missing, the google calendar event may sync only partially or fail to land as a usable notion database item.</p>\n<h3>Notion database item into Google Calendar</h3>\n<p>This flow depends on structured page properties. If the notion page stores timing in free text instead of database fields, the process cannot reliably produce the `start` and `end` values required to create a google calendar event.</p>\n<h3>Why edits create confusion</h3>\n<p>Once both systems can change the same meeting, the integration needs a stored cross-reference and a rule for which side controls each field. Without that, a normal edit can be mistaken for a new item and create duplicate records.</p>\n<h2>Where Google Calendar and Notion usually break in production</h2>\n<p>The common issues are operational, not theoretical. A record appears to sync, but a field is blank, a date range is malformed, or a rollup value never arrives because the related source was not shared with the integration.</p>\n<p>That pattern is what makes teams stop trusting the automation. They no longer assume a synced event or page is correct, so they start checking every important item by hand.</p>\n<h3>Schema mismatch on the Notion side</h3>\n<p>Use database-backed Notion pages when you need structured field mapping. Notion’s API treats database rows as pages whose properties must match the database schema, so a page outside a database/data source is a poor target for repeatable automation.</p>\n<h3>Required fields on the Google Calendar side</h3>\n<p>For Google Calendar event creation, map at least `start` and `end`. Optional fields like attendees, visibility, reminders, conference data, and attachments can be added later, but missing base timing fields will break the event request.</p>\n<h3>Sharing gaps on relation-linked records</h3>\n<p>If the workflow reads relation or rollup properties, the related parent database must also be shared with the integration. Otherwise the process may run successfully while still returning empty or partial values.</p>\n<h2>What to include in the implementation brief</h2>\n<p>A useful brief names the exact calendars, notion database objects, trigger events, and decision rules instead of saying only that Google Calendar and Notion should sync. It should identify which side is authoritative for each field and what happens when values conflict.</p>\n<p>It should also define the operational boundary of the workflow: what gets created automatically, what gets updated, what gets ignored, and where exceptions are reviewed.</p>\n<h3>Trigger choices and routing rules</h3>\n<p>Specify whether the process should react to New Google Calendar event, Google Calendar event ends, or New or updated Google Calendar event, and list which calendar each rule applies to.</p>\n<h3>Field map and required properties</h3>\n<p>Document the Notion database properties and the Google Calendar fields they map to, including title, date, start, end, attendees, status, reminders, and any visibility settings. This is where missing fields become visible before build work starts.</p>\n<h3>Failure handling and ownership</h3>\n<p>State where failed runs are logged, who reviews them, how retries work, and what documentation must be handed over so future schema changes do not require reverse-engineering the whole integration.</p>\n<h2>Why a direct replacement can be worth it</h2>\n<p>A direct implementation matters when this workflow controls meetings, deadlines, or work planning rather than simple reference data. In those cases, a bad sync changes what people see on their schedule and what they assume has been captured in Notion.</p>\n<p>It also matters when the team needs durable controls around ID matching, update filtering, permission checks, and audit visibility instead of relying on a chain of middleware steps that are hard to reason about later.</p>\n<h3>Simple logging can stay lightweight</h3>\n<p>If you are only copying a google calendar event into a notion database for reference and someone can fix occasional mismatches quickly, a lighter setup is often enough.</p>\n<h3>Two-way scheduling needs stronger rules</h3>\n<p>If a notion database item can create a google calendar event and later edits should update that same event, the process needs stored IDs, validation before writes, and explicit rules for duplicates, skipped records, and partial updates.</p>\n<h3>The handover is part of the deliverable</h3>\n<p>A solid outcome includes the field map, trigger definitions, permission prerequisites, known failure modes, and a maintenance runbook so the team can operate the workflow without depending on tribal knowledge.</p>",
